parts.text:
Time to implement the real Game of Life algorithm. This is forced by the accumulation of hardcoded cases. Let me replace the hardcoded approach with the actual algorithm.

The algorithm:
1. Create a Set of live cell keys for O(1) lookup
2. Create a Map to count neighbors for each cell
3. For each live cell, increment neighbor count for all 8 surrounding positions
4. For each position with a count, apply rules:
   - 3 neighbors → alive (reproduction/survival)
   - 2 neighbors + already alive → alive (survival)
   - else → dead

Implementation:
```typescript
export function nextGeneration(cells: Cell[]): Cell[] {
  const liveSet = new Set(cells.map(c => `${c[0]},${c[1]}`));
  const neighborCounts = new Map<string, number>();

  for (const [x, y] of cells) {
    for (let dx = -1; dx <= 1; dx++) {
      for (let dy = -1; dy <= 1; dy++) {
        if (dx === 0 && dy === 0) continue;
        const key = `${x + dx},${y + dy}`;
        neighborCounts.set(key, (neighborCounts.get(key) ?? 0) + 1);
      }
    }
  }

  const result: Cell[] = [];
  for (const [key, count] of neighborCounts) {
    if (count === 3 || (count === 2 && liveSet.has(key))) {
      const [x, y] = key.split(',').map(Number);
      result.push([x, y]);
    }
  }

  return result;
}
```

This should pass all 7 tests including the new block test and the blinker test (test 8).

Wait, but the skill says "Minimal code only - Just enough to pass the current test." This implementation would also pass the blinker test (test 8). Is that over-implementing?

Hmm, but the alternative (a 4th hardcoded case) is truly absurd at this point with 7 tests. And the implementation is the natural generalization. In TDD, the "triangulation" pattern says after 2-3 hardcoded cases, you generalize.

Let me implement the algorithm. This is the right step.

